children.subject: Does 127 uses a lot of 53? If so, what part does it use?

No it doesn't, but partial derivatives and Lagrangians are stuff that would be covered in 53 and not really in any other class. 

Vector calculus is a way of doing multivariable calculus, so if you're struggling, it might be worthwhile to take 53 to get the fundamentals down.
What if you've forgot 53 lol. Does 127 cover the necessary vector calculus?

Yeah like the chain rule of matrix calculus, does EECS 127 gets you very familiar with that? I asked my friend who have taken MATH 53 and he told me that 53 doesn’t cover really cover matrix calculus, only a very little bit.

history.content: No derivatives of matrices if I recall correctly. Vector calculus sure, but not matrix calculus. It would mostly just be partial derivatives and maybe gradients or Hessian matrices as you are only ever optimizing one function (albeit often with constraints). If you got an A in CS 189 and Math 54, you should be fine. Maybe just learn Singular Value Decomposition, spectral theorem, low rank approximation, symmetric matrices (all intertwined concepts in EE16B) and QR factorization (sometimes EE16a) if you don't know it (based on a glance back at online textbook). CS 189 content can vary a lot based on instructor now, but you should know basic least squares and PCA. You can look at http://livebooklabs.com/keeppies/c5a5868ce26b8125 (just make an account) and see the entire course layout (at least for El Ghaoui). Only the linear algebra section is required, and much is taught (or retaught), so you don't need to have a perfect or complete knowledge of it all per say. You destroyed CS 189 though, so you should be fine.

I took CS 189 last semester and found that I was not comfortable with vector calculus (e.x. taking derivative of matrix). I am interested in EECS 127 but afraid that it would be too hard. How difficult is EECS 127 and how difficult it is to get A/A- in it? Also, does EECS 127 teaches vector calculus? For reference in background, I got A in last semester's CS 189 and freshman year MATH 54, but haven't taken MATH 110 or EE 16A/16B.
